ansparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Great question! Here are your two options:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Option A — Styled Header (faster, no extra work)</strong>
I create a visually striking text-based header using your website's dark gold theme — with the title, key stats (4.83 lakh vs 2,083) and case details displayed as a designed graphic within the page itself. Looks very professional.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Option B — New Cover Image (more visual impact)</strong>
I design a cover image similar to your other articles — with a visual element representing the GSTAT/tribunal theme, the title, and your name. Matches the style of your LinkedIn covers.</p>
<hr class="border-border-200 border-t-0.5 my-3 mx-1.5">
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">My honest recommendation is <strong>Option B</strong> — a proper cover image makes the article look consistent with your other two posts and gives it more visual impact when shared. I can generate one for you right now!</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
